The final hurdle contains two ciphertexts.  The longer one is
encrypted with triple-DES in electronic code book mode.  It uses a
128-bit EDE key.

The RSA public key cryptosystem has been used to encipher the
triple-DES key; this forms the shorter ciphertext.  The public
exponent is 3735928559 in decimal and the public modulus is the
following 155-digit decimal integer:

10742 78829 12665 65907 17841 12799 42116 61266 39217 94753 29458
88778 17210 35546 41509 80121 87903 38329 26235 28109 07506 72083
50494 19964 33143 42555 83344 01855 80898 94268 92463.

Your task is to decipher the longer message and so discover the final
code word.  How you do this is up to you, but it will almost certainly
be much, much easier to break the RSA ciphertext by factoring the public
modulus than by any other approach.


=============================================================================
SOLUTION NOTES  (validate_inputs.py, solve_stage10.py)
=============================================================================

CODEWORD:  DRYDEN
           (John Dryden, 17th-century English poet, 1631-1700)


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. CIPHER SYSTEM — HYBRID RSA + DES ENCRYPTION
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Stage 10 uses a two-layer hybrid cryptosystem, the same design used in
real-world protocols such as TLS and PGP:

  Layer 1 (outer): RSA public-key encryption protects the symmetric key.
    * RSA modulus N: 512-bit (155-digit) semiprime, N = p * q
    * Public exponent e = 3,735,928,559 = 0xDEADBEEF (a playful choice
      by Simon Singh — DEADBEEF is a famous debugging magic number)
    * Encryption: C = M^e mod N, where M is the DES key
    * Shorter message file: the RSA ciphertext C (a 155-digit integer)

  Layer 2 (inner): DES symmetric-key encryption protects the actual text.
    * Cipher: Single DES in ECB (Electronic Codebook) mode, 8-byte key
    * Ciphertext: text.d — a 200-byte binary file (25 DES blocks of 8 bytes)
    * Source: longer_message_stage10.uue (UUencoded), decoded to text.d

NOTE: The README states "triple-DES with a 128-bit EDE key," but the
actual encryption is SINGLE DES.  RSA decryption yields a 16-byte value M;
only the FIRST 8 bytes form the DES key — the remaining 8 bytes are unused.
This is a deliberate misdirection (or an inconsistency in the challenge).

To decrypt, one must reverse both layers:
  Step 1: Factor the RSA modulus N into its prime factors p and q.
  Step 2: Compute the RSA private exponent d from p and q.
  Step 3: Compute M = C^d mod N to recover the DES key.
  Step 4: Decrypt text.d with M[0:8] (single DES, ECB mode) to get plaintext.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. STEP 1 — FACTORING THE RSA MODULUS (validate_inputs.py)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

The security of RSA rests entirely on the difficulty of factoring N.
A 512-bit modulus was considered secure in 1999 (when the challenge was
published), but is now within reach of a modern workstation.

The comparison point: the RSA-155 challenge (a different 512-bit number)
was first factored in 1999 by an academic team of ~300 CPU-years.
Today, a single server with many cores can do it in about a day.

Quick checks (validate_inputs.py) — tried first, took seconds:
  * Trial division up to 10^7: failed (smallest factor is ~256-bit)
  * Pollard's rho (Brent variant), 5 seeds, 10^7 iterations: failed
  * Pollard's p-1, B = 10^6: failed (p-1 is not 10^6-smooth)

These quick checks are expected to fail against cryptographic primes.
They are run as a sanity check and to rule out "easy" cases.

GNFS factorization (the actual approach):
  Tool: CADO-NFS, an open-source General Number Field Sieve implementation.
  Hardware: 64-core AMD Threadripper PRO 5995WX, 512GB RAM.
  Total wall-clock time: approximately 18.5 hours.

  GNFS phases:
    1. Polynomial Selection (size-optimized)    ~47 minutes
    2. Polynomial Selection (root-optimized)     ~5 minutes
    3. Lattice Sieving (collecting relations)   ~14 hours   <- bottleneck
    4. Filtering (deduplication, merging)       ~30 minutes
    5. Linear Algebra (Krylov / lingen / mksol)  ~2.5 hours
    6. Square Root (factor extraction)            ~3 minutes

  Command used:
    cd ~/cado-nfs
    ./cado-nfs.py $(cat N.txt) -t all

  Result (from CADO-NFS output "Square Root: Factors: <p> <q>"):
    p = 12844205165381031491662259028977553198964984323915864368216177647043137765477
    q = 836391832187606937820650856449710761904520026199724985596729108812301394489219

  Verification: p * q == N  (confirmed)


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. STEP 2 — RSA KEY RECOVERY (solve_stage10.py)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

With p and q known, computing the RSA private key is straightforward:

  phi(N) = (p - 1) * (q - 1)        Euler's totient function

  d = e^(-1) mod phi(N)              Modular inverse (Extended Euclidean)
                                     Python 3.8+: d = pow(e, -1, phi_N)

  M = C^d mod N                      RSA decryption (square-and-multiply)

The recovered plaintext M as a 16-byte big-endian integer:
  M = 0x462c6bad381031ad 64dccd9820a751a2

Verification: M^e mod N == C  (round-trip confirmed)


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. STEP 3 — DES KEY EXTRACTION AND DECRYPTION (solve_stage10.py)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

M is 16 bytes, but only the first 8 bytes form the DES key:
  DES key: 0x462c6bad381031ad

The script (solve_stage10.py) tries all plausible key extraction strategies:
  Approach A: Textbook RSA — key is the low/high/all bytes of M, in various
              alignments (8, 16, 24 bytes).
  Approach B: PKCS#1 v1.5 — check for 0x00 0x02 padding header in M (not
              present here; M starts with 0x00 0x00).
  Approach C: Little-endian byte order — in case byte ordering was reversed.

Each candidate key is tried against the 200-byte DES ciphertext (text.d).
Success is detected automatically: a key that produces English plaintext
will have > 85% printable bytes AND > 40% common English letters.  Wrong
keys produce pseudorandom output (~37% printable), giving effectively zero
false-positive rate.

The winning candidate: "First 8 bytes of M" with single DES ECB.
  Printable: 99%   English: YES


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. CRYPTOGRAPHIC PARAMETERS SUMMARY
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

  RSA modulus N   : 512-bit semiprime (155 decimal digits)
  Public exponent : e = 3,735,928,559 = 0xDEADBEEF
  RSA ciphertext  : shorter_message_stage10.txt (155-digit integer)
  Factorization   : CADO-NFS GNFS, ~18.5 hours on 64-core workstation
  Factors         : p (77 digits, 256 bits), q (78 digits, 256 bits)
  DES key         : 462c6bad381031ad  (8 bytes = 64 bits, 56 effective)
  DES mode        : ECB (Electronic Codebook)
  DES ciphertext  : text.d (200 bytes = 25 blocks)


